 houses in the northeast often patronized visiting performers and might be aware of developments in the capital, the region also had lively performance traditions of its own, on every level of society, from the wedding revels, sporting activities, and household fools of major noble families, through civic plays and processions, to the customary annual performances of hunters and ploughmen. The book considers the political, economic, religious, and psychological impulses that affected these traditions, and its closing chapter addresses their possible relevance to the culture of the region today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish dramaxHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aEntertainersxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland, North East. 0aTheaterxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland, North East. 7aDRAMA / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Heritage.  aFolk Ceremonies.  aMedieval performance.  aMinistralli.  aNorthumberland.  aRevels.  aRush-bearings.  aStuart Performance.  aTravelling Players.  aTudor Performance.  aYorkshire.  anorth-east England.1 aAlexander, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckett, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakovac, Gašper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlausner, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKinnell, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcgee, C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckinnell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRavelhofer, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Sylvia, econtri